        "id": "art_2026-07-04_021",
        "section": "The Americas",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "The Caribbean has a problem with pesticides",
        "title_zh": "加勒比地区面临农药难题:单位面积用量冠绝全球",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-04/21",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n加勒比地区虽农药总用量不大,但单位面积使用强度冠绝全球,管理松散叠加农民缺乏培训,正造成沉重的健康、环境与经济代价。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n1. **强度而非总量才是核心症结**:据联合国粮农组织(FAO)统计,加勒比岛屿包揽全球单位面积农药用量前十名中的五席;圣卢西亚每公顷用量是美国的十倍,特立尼达和多巴哥是俄罗斯的三十倍,而巴西一周的农药用量就超过加勒比全年。\n2. **高强度使用存在客观原因**:高温高湿助长害虫杂草、丘陵地形削弱药效、劳动力短缺迫使农民以化学除草替代人工、小市场难以获得天然替代品、殖民地遗留的种植园作物易染病,且欧洲买家只接受外观完美的果品(安提瓜和巴布达监管者乔纳·奥蒙)。\n3. **浪费与麻痹并存**:农民训练严重不足,常在虫害失控后才察觉,且无法准确诊断,导致错用药物、错时施药、错配剂量(FAO的梅尔文·梅迪纳·纳瓦罗);安提瓜年轻农民Teek甚至通过YouTube学配药;政府监管松懈,仅少数国家禁用百草枯(中国、巴西、欧盟早已禁用),其主要生产商正因美国帕金森病诉讼而停产。\n4. **健康代价沉重**:加勒比地区前列腺癌与多发性骨髓瘤发病率偏高,均被认为与长期农药暴露相关;农药易获取也被视为推高自杀率的因素之一(英国农药自杀预防中心的加米尼·马努维拉)。\n5. **生态与土壤破坏严重**:除草剂汇入河流海湾,致使鱼类死亡、珊瑚礁白化;空容器随意丢弃,危害牲畜与野生动物;农药逐步杀灭蚯蚓、细菌等土壤有益生物(安提瓜农民迈克尔·约瑟夫);瓜德罗普与马提尼克数十年后仍受禁用杀虫剂氯丹酮(chlordecone)污染,该物质可在环境中残留长达600年(法国Inserm的吕克·穆尔蒂尼耶)。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议,主要呈现的是加勒比地区农药过度使用的现状及其多维度代价。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n若监管与培训持续缺位,加勒比地区癌症高发、自杀及珊瑚礁退化等问题或将延续数十年;氯丹酮等长效污染物的存在意味着,部分岛屿可能在未来数百年仍受农药遗留问题困扰。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">The Americas</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | Pick your poison</span></p>\n<h1>The Caribbean has a problem with pesticides</h1>\n<h3>It uses them more intensively than anywhere in the world</h3>\n<h3>July 2nd 2026</h3>\n<p>TEEK IS ALARMINGLY relaxed about the noxious substances he uses to make sure his watermelons survive. The young farmer in Antigua is whipping up a toxic brew, mixing ingredients as if preparing a rum cocktail. Where did he learn this delicate art? “YouTube,” he says. He and his cousin go on to drench a four-acre field with their marvellous medicine. Such scenes are common in the Caribbean. It has become a hotspot for pesticide misuse.</p>\n<p>The problem is not the total stock of pesticides that the region gets through: Brazil scatters more chemicals in a week than the Caribbean does in a year. Nor is it about toxicity: African countries possess deadlier stockpiles of obsolete or highly hazardous pesticides (HHPs). The challenge in the Caribbean is the intensity with which these poisons are administered. Caribbean islands dominate use per hectare, says the UN’s Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO). They make up five of the world’s top ten users. Hectare-for-hectare, Saint Lucia sprinkles ten times more than the United States (see chart). Trinidad &amp; Tobago uses 30 times as much as Russia.</p>\n<p>There are some good reasons for this. Heat and humidity stimulate pests and weeds. Hilly terrain makes pesticides less effective. Labour shortages increase the incentive for farmers to weed using chemicals. Small markets limit access to natural alternatives that are used elsewhere, says Jonah Ormond, a regulator in Antigua &amp; Barbuda. The plantation crops left behind by colonials are highly vulnerable to disease. And the European shops that buy them will take only perfect produce. </p>\n<p>Yet waste and complacency also play a part. Many of the region’s farmers are poorly trained; they don’t detect pests until they are running amok. Even then, they can’t always diagnose what problem they have, says Melvin Medina Navarro of the FAO. So they use the wrong substances, at the wrong time, in the wrong dose.</p>\n<p>Governments in the region have been lax about deciding which pesticides farmers should use. Only a few Caribbean countries and dependencies have banned paraquat, a notorious herbicide long prohibited in Brazil, China and the EU. Its main manufacturer is now stopping production amid lawsuits in America claiming links to Parkinson’s disease.</p>\n<p>The costs of all this are large. The Caribbean has high rates of prostate cancer and multiple myeloma, both of which are thought to be made more likely by long-term exposure to pesticides. Easy availability of pesticides contributes to high suicide rates, thinks Gamini Manuweera of the Centre for Pesticide Suicide Prevention in Britain. People use it to kill themselves.</p>\n<p>Weedkillers run into rivers and bays, killing fish and bleaching coral reefs. Empty containers are dumped, harming livestock and wildlife. Treatments are making soil gradually worse, by killing off things such as worms and bacteria that nourish it, says Michael Joseph, an Antiguan farmer.</p>\n<p>Guadeloupe and Martinique are still contaminated with the dangerous insecticide chlordecone decades after its prohibition, notes Luc Multigner of Inserm, a French medical-research agency. That limits what they can grow. It can hang around for 600 years. So the Caribbean may face pesticide problems for centuries yet. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//the-americas/2026/07/02/the-caribbean-has-a-problem-with-pesticides\">https://www.economist.com//the-americas/2026/07/02/the-caribbean-has-a-problem-with-pesticides</a> </p>"
